# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: new-zealand
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] The **1853 New Zealand general election** was a nationwide vote to determine the shape of the New Zealand Parliament's first term.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] It was the first national election ever held in New Zealand, although Parliament did not yet have full authority to govern the colony, which was part of the British Empire at that time.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] Elections for the first provincial councils and their Superintendents were held at the same time.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] The New Zealand Constitution Act 1852, passed by the Parliament of the United Kingdom, established a bicameral New Zealand Parliament, with the lower house (the House of Representatives) being elected by popular vote.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] Votes were to be cast under a simple FPP system, and the secret ballot had not yet been introduced.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] To qualify as a voter, one needed to be male, to be a British subject, to be at least 21 years old, to own a certain value of land, and to not be serving a criminal sentence.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] One of the candidates elected (on 27 August, for Christchurch Country) was a landowner, but at 20 years and 7 months was not yet 21: he was James Stuart-Wortley.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] At the time of the 1853 elections, there were no political parties in New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] As such, all candidates were independents.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] In the 1853 elections, election day was different in each seat.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] The first seat to be elected was Bay of Islands on 14 July, and the final election day was on 1 October.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] Hugh Carleton (Bay of Islands) was the first MP ever elected in New Zealand (though he was elected unopposed), so he liked to be called the Father of the House.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] There were 5,849 people registered to vote.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] Twenty-four electoral districts were used.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] Some districts elected multiple MPs (they elected using block voting).
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] Wellington and Auckland had three members each.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] Suburbs of Auckland, Christchurch, Dunedin, Hutt, Nelson, Northern, Pensioner, Southern and Waimea each had two members.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] Thirteen members were elected in single-member districts using first past the post.
[src:new-zealand/1853-new-zealand-general-election] Some parts of the colony were not part of any district and did not have representation in Parliament.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] The **Sewell ministry** was the first responsible government in New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] Unlike previous executives, its members were held accountable to Parliament.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] This would form the basis for future governments in New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] The ministry formed in 1856, but lasted only one month, from 18 April to 20 May.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] From 7 May onwards, Henry Sewell held office as colonial secretary, considered to be the equivalent of a prime minister or premier.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] Thus, Sewell is regarded as the first prime minister of New Zealand.It was replaced by the Fox Ministry on May 20th 1856.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] It also allowed for provinces to be formed, each presided over by an elected superintendent, for initially Auckland, Taranaki, Wellington, Nelson, Canterbury and Otago.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] Elections were held in 1853 for the provincial councils, the superintendents, and the House of Representatives.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] In this federal system, the central government had responsibility over defence and native affairs, and the provincial governments had substantial powers of their own.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] The system of government was set up at a time when European settlements were scattered and small, and communications and travel were rather difficult.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] Virtually all long distance travel and transport of goods was by sea.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] To be eligible to vote in either the provincial or national elections, voters had to be male owners of property valued at £50, or leasehold valued at £10.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] The first Parliament had 37 members, elected by 5849 voters, of which around 100 were Maori.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] Once the provincial governments had been set up, New Zealand had given itself six miniature parliaments, endeavouring to emulate Westminster as best they could, for a total European population of about 30,000.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] And all of that in addition to the bicameral Parliament.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] At the first meeting of Parliament in May 1854, a resolution was passed that the House be given responsible and representative government immediately, i.e. the power to appoint an Executive Council that has decision-making powers.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] Robert Wynyard, the administrator filling in after Grey's departure and before the arrival of the next governor, Colonel Thomas Gore Browne, formed an Executive Council led by James FitzGerald (the Fitzgerald ministry).
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] When it became clear that the first ministers had no power, they resigned as the Executive after seven weeks.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] Wynyard prorogued Parliament as the members refused to accept his claim that responsible government was not possible without royal assent, which had not been given.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] In the next session, Thomas Forsaith, a member of the minority that supported Wynyard, was appointed by Wynyard to lead an Executive (the Forsaith ministry).
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] This appointed ministry did not have the confidence of Parliament and lasted only from 31 August to 2 September 1854.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] When Browne arrived, he announced that self-government would begin with the 2nd New Zealand Parliament.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] Henry Sewell, who had been a member of the 1st Parliament, stood for re-election in the Town of Christchurch electorate, and was returned.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] As a result of his previous service on Fitzgerald's first Executive Council, Sewell was asked by Browne to form a government.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] He was appointed to the Executive Council on 18 April 1856, and became Colonial Secretary (considered to be the equivalent of Prime Minister), at the head of New Zealand's first responsible government, on 7 May.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] Dillon Bell became Colonial Treasurer, Frederick Whitaker became Attorney-General, and Henry Tancred became a minister without portfolio.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] Whitaker and Tancred were both members of the Legislative Council.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] Previously, the Executive Council had functioned as an advisory group to the governor, and ministerial functions were performed by appointed officials, not politicians.
[src:new-zealand/1856-sewell-ministry] The various "ministers" serving on the Council, such as Andrew Sinclair (Colonial Secretary since 1844) and Alexander Shepherd (Colonial Treasurer since 1842), retired from their roles.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The **1888–89 New Zealand Native football team** was a New Zealand rugby union team that toured Britain, Ireland, Australia and New Zealand in 1888 and 1889.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] It mostly comprised players of Māori ancestry, but also included some Pākehā (white New Zealanders).
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] A wholly private endeavour, the tour was not under the auspices of any official rugby authority; it was organised by New Zealand international player Joe Warbrick, promoted by public servant Thomas Eyton, and managed by James Scott, a publican.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives were the first New Zealand team to perform a haka, and also the first to wear all black.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] They played 107 rugby matches during the tour, as well as a small number of Victorian Rules football matches in Australia.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Having made a significant impact on the development of New Zealand rugby, the Natives were inducted into the World Rugby Hall of Fame in 2008.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] After a preliminary tour of New Zealand in 1888, the side travelled to England via Melbourne and Suez.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Māori players initially provoked curiosity due to their race, but the British press subsequently expressed some surprise that the side was not as "Māori" as they had expected.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Playing their first match, on 3 October against Surrey, the team was subjected to a taxing match schedule, and frequently played three matches per week.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Their early matches included a 9–0 loss to Middlesex, but their form improved in November, when they won 10 of their 13 matches.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team played its first match against a national team on 1 December, against Ireland, and won 13–4.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] This was followed by a win over one of the strongest English county teams, Yorkshire, and a 5–0 defeat against the Wales national team.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] By January 1889 the Natives had played 36 matches in less than three months, winning 22 of them; they had spent most of their time in the north of England, where the playing strength was strongest and the crowds largest and most profitable.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] In a return match on 19 January, Yorkshire fielded a stronger side than in the first match and inflicted one of the Natives' heaviest losses, a 16–4 defeat.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team then went undefeated until 16 February, when they faced England.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives apologised afterwards for their behaviour, but the damage remained.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The New Zealanders left England without an official send-off, and travelled to Australia where they toured Victoria, New South Wales and Queensland.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] They then returned to New Zealand, where they displayed a level of combination not seen in their home country before.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] They went 31 games undefeated before losing their final match, on 24 August 1889, 7–2 to Auckland.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives' final record in rugby matches was 78 wins, 6 draws and 23 losses.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] They introduced tactical innovations to New Zealand rugby on their return home, and their tour contributed to the formation of the New Zealand Rugby Football Union in 1892.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Seventeen of the team's 26 players went on to play provincially in New Zealand, and two, Thomas Ellison and David Gage, subsequently captained the New Zealand national rugby team.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The idea for assembling a team of Māori footballers to tour Britain was conceived by Joseph Warbrick, a rugby player who had toured with the first New Zealand national team in 1884.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] He initially proposed a team of Māori or part-Māori to play the touring British side in 1888; this developed into a venture to have a Māori team tour Britain if a preliminary tour of New Zealand were successful.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Hearing of Warbrick's plans, public servant Thomas Eyton contacted him to offer help managing the tour, which Warbrick accepted.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] When James Scott, a publican, subsequently joined the partnership, the three men decided that Warbrick would be the team's captain, Scott its manager and Eyton its promoter.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Warbrick started assembling a team for the tour in early 1888.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] He had difficulties assembling a squad due to player availability, and failed to secure the talented Jack Taiaroa due to his university commitments.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Some Māori players who initially agreed to play later pulled out when the eligibility criteria were relaxed to allow squad members who were only part-Māori.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Twenty Māori or part-Māori players joined the squad; five Pākehā (white New Zealand) players were added after the team lost to Auckland.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Due to the inclusion of these Pākehā players the team was renamed from the "New Zealand Maori" to the "New Zealand Native Football Representatives".
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The final squad comprised 26 players (including Warbrick); of these at least five were full-blooded Māori, while fourteen had a Māori mother and a Pākehā father.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The parentage of some of the players is unknown.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team toured New Zealand before departing overseas, playing against Hawke's Bay, Auckland, Nelson, Wellington, Canterbury, South Canterbury, and Otago.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The first game was contested against Hawke's Bay in Napier on 23 June 1888.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] They played nine games in their preliminary tour of New Zealand, and won seven of them.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Their last New Zealand match before departure, against Otago played in Dunedin on 31 July 1888, was won by one try to nil.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team sailed for Australia from Dunedin, leaving on 1 August 1888.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] In Melbourne, Scott recruited Jack Lawlor to train the players in Victorian Rules football in Britain as preparation for possible Victorian Rules matches on their return to Australia.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team played two rugby matches against the Melbourne Rugby Union team, winning the first and drawing the second, before continuing to Britain via Suez.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] They arrived in London on 27 September 1888.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team were met in Britain by local rugby administrators, including an official of England's Rugby Football Union (RFU).
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The first match of the tour was against Surrey, where the team became the first New Zealand side to perform a haka, and also the first to wear an all black uniform.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] That the team was predominantly Māori provoked curiosity from the British press – at the time, most Britons had not seen non-white people – but there was some surprise that the team were not as "Māori" as had been expected.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] "They are not unlike Europeans," a Scottish reporter wrote in November 1888; "that is their resemblance is great when one remembers that they were a savage tribe no further back than a generation".
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Surrey match, which was refereed by the RFU secretary George Rowland Hill, was won 4–1 by the Natives after they scored two tries.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives next defeated both Northamptonshire and Kent, before defeats by Moseley and Burton-on-Trent.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Both defeats were unexpected, and in the Moseley match, injuries played a part – the tourists played most of the match at least two men down, as replacements were then not allowed.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team recovered to win their next game, against Midlands Counties in Birmingham.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Their next fixture was against Middlesex in a match not open to the public, and hosted by the Earl of Sheffield at Sheffield Park, Uckfield.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Middlesex side contained a number of international players, including Arthur Gould.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Middlesex won easily, with the Natives play characterised by poor tackling.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The final score was 9–0, with three tries conceded by the New Zealanders.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Prior to the match both sides had enjoyed lunch with wine – an indulgence the Natives were not used to.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Following the match against Middlesex, the team travelled to the north, where the strongest English rugby teams were based.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Yorkshire and Lancashire dominated the county championship until many of their respective member clubs split from the RFU in 1895 over the issue of "broken time" payments.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] 1–0, defeated Dewsbury, then lost to Wakefield Trinity.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] After their first draw of the tour (against Northumberland County) they defeated Stockton-on-Tees and Tynemouth.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Joe Warbrick appeared in the match against Tynemouth, but aggravated the foot injury that had kept him out of the side until that point.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] These victories were followed by a 13–4 defeat to Halifax on 10 November.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team then won seven matches in a row, including one against Hawick RFC, their only Scottish opposition of the tour.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The last two matches that month were a loss to Swinton and a 9–0 victory over Liverpool and District.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team had played thirteen fixtures during November and won ten of them.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] By this point, the team was beset by injuries – of the 15 players that played against Westmorland County on 24 November, five had injuries.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The squad comprised only 26 players, and the tourists were often struggling to field a side.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Nevertheless, their heavy schedule continued; on 30 November 1888 they left for Dublin, where a match had been organised against the Ireland national team.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Ireland fixture was played at Lansdowne Road, Dublin, on 1 December 1888.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Both teams had a number of leading players out injured – the Irish were forced to make four changes to their original selection.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Ireland led 3–0 at half-time after scoring a converted try, but the Natives improved considerably in the second-half, scoring four tries.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Patrick Keogh scored the first two tries, and his play was praised by the local press.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The third try scored was by Thomas Ellison after a counter-attack by George Williams.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The try was not converted, but the strong finish from the New Zealanders gave the visitors a 13–4 victory.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Irish press were surprised by the loss and strongly criticised their team, but Ireland did go on to defeat Wales two tries to nil in the 1889 Home Nations Championship.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Following their defeat of Ireland, the Natives played Trinity College and then North of Ireland.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The match against Trinity College was drawn 4–4, and despite Keogh not playing, the Native side played much better than their previous fixture.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team then travelled to Belfast, where they defeated North of Ireland 2–0 on 5 December; scoring two tries to nil.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] After returning to England, the Natives faced Lancashire in Manchester, where they lost 1–0.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Two days later they drew with Batley, despite their opposition scoring five tries.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Their next match was against Yorkshire, who were one of the strongest counties in the country, and went on to win the inaugural County Championship that season.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Yorkshire fielded a weakened team, and were subsequently defeated 10–6 by the Natives, who scored six tries.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] After a further two victories, the team travelled to Wales, where they lost 3–0 to Llanelli, before facing Wales on 22 December.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] At the start of the match the home crowd were fairly hostile towards the Welsh team due to fans of both Swansea and Llanelli feeling slighted by the lack of selection of their players.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Four teams dominated Welsh national selection at the time, and out of the 15-man team only William Towers and William Bowen of Swansea and Dan Griffiths of Llanelli had been selected.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The match was played in Swansea, and the lack of local players may have contributed to a poor crowd, with gate receipts of only £120 recorded.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The crowd's hostility impacted on the players, and debutant Norman Biggs was "palpably nervous" at the start of the match.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Biggs, aged 18 years and 49 days, became the youngest Welsh international player – a record he held until the debut of Tom Prydie in 2010.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Despite the heckles aimed primarily at Biggs, Charlie Arthur and George Thomas, the Welsh team produced an excellent effort, especially from the forwards.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Towers scored the first Welsh try, which was converted by Jim Webb.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives replied with a spirited run by Ellison, but he failed to break through the Welsh defence.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The tourists trailed even further after George Thomas scored a breakaway try from the half-way line, which went some way to silence the heckles from the crowd.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Webb, playing in out of position at full-back, missed the conversion and then failed at a long-distance goal from a mark.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives continued to push, with Elliot coming within five-yards of the try line, and when Ellison did manage to cross the line he was carried back into the 25-yard line before he could touch down.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] In the second half Wales continued to push their advantage when Alexander Bland dribbled the ball into the Natives' 25; this was collected by Sydney Nicholls, who managed to get the ball across the try line, allowing Jim Hannan to score.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Warbrick for the Natives and Stadden for Wales both subsequently came close to scoring tries, but there were no further scores in the game.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The match was also of historical importance because of the Welsh tactics employed.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] In the 1886 Home Nations Championship Wales had trialled the four three-quarter system, wherein the team would play with eight forwards rather than nine, and instead employ an extra centre three-quarter.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The system was deemed a failure and was particularly unpopular with star Welsh player Arthur Gould, whose formidable ability as a back allowed his club team Newport to retain the additional forward.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] With Gould working in the West Indies, Wales again tried the four three-quarter system against the Natives, and its success saw the team permanently adopt the system.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Within six years the other three Home Countries had adopted four three-quarter style of play.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Before they left Wales, the Natives played Swansea and two other local clubs, Newport, and Cardiff.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] They defeated Swansea for their first win in Wales, and followed this up with a victory over Newport in front of 8,000 spectators.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] They finished their Welsh matches, and the year, with a 4–1 loss to Cardiff in front of a partisan crowd.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The side entered 1889 having played 36 matches for 22 wins and three draws.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives' play had improved throughout November and December following poorer form in their October matches; positive press reports reflected this improvement.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team would go on to play a further 17 matches before their 16 February match against England.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] January started with a 4–1 loss to Bradford, during which 25 police officers were required to keep many of the 12,000 spectators, many of them non-paying, in order.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] This was followed by victories over Leeds Parish Church, Kirkstall, Brighouse Rangers, and Huddersfield.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Following further matches against Stockport, Castleford, and Warrington, where the team drew, lost, then won, the side faced Yorkshire for a second time.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Yorkshire had been criticised in the press for fielding a weakened line-up against the Natives when the sides first met in December.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] After the unexpected loss, Yorkshire were determined to make amends and a strong side was selected for the county, including Fred Bonsor, Richard Lockwood and John Willie Sutcliffe, all of whom would appear for England against the Natives later that season.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Described as "knocked about" and "stale", the Natives struggled to compete against such strong opposition, and Yorkshire scored three converted tries before a try to Ellison left the scores at 9–1 at half-time.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The second half was little better for the Natives; they conceded a further two tries as well as a drop-goal.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The second of these tries was scored by Lockwood after he ran the ball from his own half.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Ellison scored a converted try late in the match, but this didn't prevent the Natives suffering their largest defeat of the tour: 16–4 to the Yorkshiremen.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Ellison later described the match as "without a murmur, the biggest beating we received in our whole tour".
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] After a victory over Spen Valley District, the team travelled west to play Somersetshire, Devonshire, Taunton, and Gloucestershire, and won all five games.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The victory over Somerset was the New Zealanders' largest of the tour; they scored nine tries in a 17–4 victory.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Half-back Keogh played outstandingly for the Natives, while the entire side demonstrated superior passing and combination to their opposition.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Devonshire and Taunton suffered heavy defeats by the New Zealanders, before a strong Gloucestershire side was dismissed.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] After defeating Midland Counties, the Natives returned to London.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team had two further matches before their game against England.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The first was against one of the strongest clubs in England, Blackheath.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Andrew Stoddart, who had toured New Zealand and Australia with the 1888 British Isles side, played for the club in their 9–3 defeat to the Natives.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The New Zealanders won having scored four tries, including two by Keogh.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Their next opposition was a United Services side mainly comprising Royal Navy players.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives were again victorious, this time 10–0.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The match against Oxford University was postponed due to heavy frost, and so the team had a seven-day break from playing – their longest of the tour.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The match against England was causing the Natives' players and management problems before it had even begun.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team manager, Scott, was in dispute with the RFU over where the match should be played – the RFU were adamant that the match should take place at Blackheath's ground, but Scott wanted the game to proceed at The Oval, where a larger crowd, and therefore higher gate receipts, could be secured.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The strictly amateur RFU establishment were already suspicious of the profit-making motives of the Natives, and were unwilling to yield on the selection of venue.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The RFU was also in dispute with the other Home Unions over the formation of the International Rugby Football Board (IRFB).
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Ireland, Wales and Scotland consequently refused to play against England until 1891, when, following arbitration, the RFU relented and joined the IRFB.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The absence of international matches was a factor in England agreeing to face the Natives on 16 February 1889.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The line-ups selected for the 16 February match were both strong, and close to full strength.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Though 12 of the England side had not played internationally before, all were experienced at domestic level.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The match was refereed by Rowland Hill, who had also officiated the Natives' first match in Britain, against Surrey.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The opening of the first half was a scoreless affair, with much tackling and scrummaging on the heavy ground.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Later in the half England scored two tries through Harry Bedford, but both were disputed by the Natives, who claimed that one of their players had grounded the ball in-goal.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] England took the two-try advantage into the second half.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Early in the second half a third disputed try was scored by the English.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The try and its aftermath caused controversy and a rift between the Natives and the RFU.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Ellison attempted to tackle the English player Stoddart, and in the process ripped his shorts off.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives quickly formed a circle around Stoddart to allow him to replace his clothing without being seen.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] While this was happening one of the English players, Frank Evershed, picked up the ball and scored a try.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The New Zealanders protested, believing that play had stopped after claiming Stoddart had called "dead ball" – but Hill awarded the try, prompting three of the Native players, Dick Taiaroa, Williams, and Sherry Wynyard, to leave the field in protest.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The aggrieved players were eventually persuaded to return, but not before Hill had restarted play.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Ellison was very critical of Hill, particularly because he was also Secretary of the RFU.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Ellison wrote after the tour that "gross as these errors were, they were insignificant when compared with another that Mr Hill committed at the outset of the game, viz, refereeing at all in that game".
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The disputed try was followed by a final try for the English, who ultimately won 7–0.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The RFU, at Hill's instigation, promptly demanded an apology from the Natives' captain of the day, Edward McCausland, who had led the team as Joe Warbrick was injured.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The English authorities of the time believed that the decision of a referee was above question, and that protesting a decision as the New Zealanders had done was unsportsmanlike.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The RFU threatened to bar any of their affiliated players – in other words, the entire rugby playing population of England – from facing the Natives if they did not apologise.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The London establishment that governed the game were disturbed by the New Zealanders' approach to the game; reports of rough and over-aggressive play by the Natives had steadily increased in frequency since their arrival in Britain.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] In the north of England, criticism of the visitors' sportsmanship was rarer; the tourists were accepted as playing the game in the same spirit as their local opponents, which in the north was a more working class sport than in the south.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Some of the Natives, including Joe Warbrick, accused the RFU and the English press of hypocrisy, claiming that they were quick to criticise the New Zealanders for rough play, yet tolerant of similar behaviour from their own players.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives remained in London following the England match.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] They defeated London Welsh on 18 February, before losing first to Cambridge, then Oxford University.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] From there they travelled north and won two matches before losing to Leigh.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] After a win over Runcorn, there was a defeat to Oldham, played on a ground Eyton said was so frozen it was dangerous.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] After reversing their previous loss to Halifax with a 6–0 win, the Natives suffered a loss to Barrow and District on 7 March.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The New Zealanders then had a run of seven straight wins before a 1–1 draw with Hull.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Widnes were then defeated for the second time in two weeks in the tourists' last match in northern England.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team struggled to find an opponent for their final match in Britain.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] They eventually played Southern Counties, and beat them 3–1.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] This was their 74th match in the British Isles and their 49th victory.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The authorities and press in London continued to view the team negatively, and the Natives boarded ship without a formal farewell.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] This perceived affront from the RFU provoked some criticism from the press outside London, as well as from the team manager Scott, who felt that with the team's official apology after the England match, the controversy should have put to rest.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The majority of the Natives left Plymouth on 29 March (Eyton and Pie Wynyard followed a week later).
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] They arrived in Melbourne in May, where the team played mostly Victorian Rules football, hoping to make more money that way.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Although the side had employed Jack Lawlor to coach them in Victorian Rules during their tour of the British Isles, the heavy schedule and high injury count had left little time and energy for such training.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The side played eleven Victorian Rules matches in total, including three in New South Wales, but won only three of them, all against relatively weak opposition.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The side's success in their rugby matches contrasted to their failure in Victorian Rules – the New Zealanders played three rugby matches while in Victoria: against Melbourne, a Navy selection, and Victoria.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The matches were all won, with their game against Victoria a 19–0 victory.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] After this they left for Sydney for further rugby matches, and defeated New South Wales 12–9.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] After two further victories, the side again faced New South Wales, and won the match 16–12.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Another two victories followed, before the team played two further Victorian Rules matches against the Northumberland club in Maitland and a representative Northern Districts side in Newcastle.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team travelled north to Queensland, where, as in New South Wales, rugby was the dominant code of football.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Consequently, the team exclusively played rugby while in the region.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives faced Queensland at the Association Ground in Brisbane.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The 8000 spectators witnessed the New Zealanders overwhelm the Queenslanders to win 22–0; the Natives did not exert themselves in the win, and the score did not reflect their dominance.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] After a further two matches, against Toowoomba and Ipswich (both of whom were comfortably defeated), the team returned to Brisbane for a rematch with Queensland.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] In contrast to their first meeting, the first half was a close affair, and the two sides were tied at the conclusion of the half.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Billy Warbrick suffered a kick to the head, and had to retire early in the second-half.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Following the loss of Warbrick, the play of the Natives improved and they recovered to win 11–7.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Not long after the game concluded rumours circulated that some of the players had been offered £50 by bookmakers to throw the game.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The response from the team's management was to suspend four players.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team travelled to Toowoomba, where they defeated the locals 19–0.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives included a replacement player for only the second time, Henry Speakman, after the suspensions reduced the playing strength of the side.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The team then travelled back to New Zealand, and arrived in Invercargill on 5 August.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Two days after their return, the Natives faced Southland, who they defeated 5–1 in front of a crowd of 2,000.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The side suffered further injury, to Harry Lee, and recruited Southlander W.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Hirst for their match against Mataura District on 8 August.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Despite playing the match two players down, the Natives comfortably defeated Mataura 16–3.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Following the side's return to New Zealand, the Otago Rugby Football Union demanded that the team's management explain the accusations levelled at them in Queensland.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Eyton responded by insisting that the players had only been suspended while an investigation was conducted, and that the management was confident no wrongdoing had occurred.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] It is unlikely, given the attitude of the Otago Rugby Union to the Natives before their departure, that they would have dismissed the allegations if incriminating evidence had existed.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The side was back to full strength following the return of their suspended players when the side faced Otago in Dunedin.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives outscored their opponents five tries to two, and won 11–8.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The side's star player and half-back, Keogh, stayed in Dunedin when the team departed for Christchurch.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The side faced Hawke's Bay, who were touring, in Christchurch, and handily defeated them 13–2.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives' play was praised by *The Press*: "... the wearers of the black passed with remarkable accuracy and quickness between their legs, over their shoulders, under their arms and with their feet".
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The side then faced Canterbury on 17 August, who they thrashed 15–0.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The side left Christchurch and travelled north where they played Wairarapa in Masterton.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The match was won 10–8, and the next day they faced Wellington, who they also defeated.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The fixture against Wellington was nearly abandoned because Scott and the Wellington Rugby Union could not agree on a venue; the match went ahead only when the Wellington officials agreed to cede the Natives all profit from the match.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] After this the Natives travelled to Auckland where they played their last match, against the province on 24 August.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The match was lost 7–2 after each team scored two tries each, but the Aucklanders kicked a drop-goal and a conversion.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The loss ended a remarkable run of matches – the Natives had a 31-game unbeaten streak in rugby matches that started with their victory over Widnes on 9 March; the side won 30, and drew one match between the defeats.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The tour had a significant impact on the development of rugby within New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] It was the first tour of the British Isles by a team from the Southern Hemisphere, and the longest in the history of the sport.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] By the time the Natives returned to New Zealand, they had developed into a side superior to any in the country, and introduced a number of tactical innovations.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] Seventeen of the 26 players went on to play provincially in New Zealand, and two, Ellison and David Gage, subsequently captained New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The tour also prompted the eventual formation of the New Zealand Rugby Football Union (NZRFU, later renamed New Zealand Rugby) in 1892; one reason for its formation was to ensure greater control over any future touring New Zealand sides.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The NZRFU sent an officially sanctioned New Zealand team, captained by Ellison, to tour Australia in 1893.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Natives are also the forefathers of the Māori All Blacks, a representative team organised by the NZRFU, that first played in 1910.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The Native team, along with Joe Warbrick, was inducted into the World Rugby Hall of Fame in 2008 – the seventh inductee.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The exact names of several of the players is unknown.
[src:new-zealand/1888-89-new-zealand-native-football-team] The number of matches played is a minimum number only – the line-ups for a number of matches in Britain and Australia are either incomplete or unknown.
[src:new-zealand/1926-imperial-conference] The **1926 Imperial Conference** was the fifth Imperial Conference bringing together the prime ministers of the Dominions of the British Empire.
[src:new-zealand/1926-imperial-conference] It was held in London from 19 October to 23 November 1926.
[src:new-zealand/1926-imperial-conference] The conference was notable for producing the Balfour Declaration, which established the principle that the dominions are all equal in status, and "autonomous communities within the British Empire" not subordinate to the United Kingdom.
[src:new-zealand/1926-imperial-conference] The term "Commonwealth" was officially adopted to describe the community.
[src:new-zealand/1926-imperial-conference] The conference was arranged to follow directly after the 1926 Assembly of the League of Nations (in Geneva, Switzerland), to reduce the amount of travelling required for the dominions' representatives.
[src:new-zealand/1926-imperial-conference] The conference created the Inter-Imperial Relations Committee, chaired by Arthur Balfour, to look into future constitutional arrangements for the Commonwealth.
[src:new-zealand/1926-imperial-conference] In the end, the committee rejected the idea of a codified constitution, as espoused by South Africa's former Prime Minister Jan Smuts, but also fell short of endorsing the "end of empire" espoused by Smuts's arch-rival, Barry Hertzog.
[src:new-zealand/1926-imperial-conference] The recommendations were adopted unanimously by the conference on 15 November, followed by an equally warm reception in the newspapers.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:new-zealand/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] The **1979 oil crisis**, sometimes referred to as the **second oil crisis** (in reference to the 1973 oil crisis), refers to the drop in oil production in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution that led to an energy crisis in 1979.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Although the global oil supply only decreased by approximately four percent, the oil markets' reaction raised the price of crude oil drastically over the next 12 months, more than doubling it to $39.50 per barrel ($248/m3), equivalent to $175 per barrel ($1,101/m3) in 2025.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] The sudden increase in price was connected with fuel shortages similar to the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] In 1980, following the onset of the Iran–Iraq War, oil production in Iran fell drastically.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Iraq's oil production also dropped significantly, triggering economic recessions worldwide.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Oil prices did not return to pre-crisis levels until the mid-1980s.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Oil prices after 1980 began a steady decline over the next 20 years, except for a brief uptick during the Gulf War, which then reached a 60% fall-off in the 1990s.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Mexico, Nigeria, and Venezuela's major oil exporters expanded their production during this time.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] The Soviet Union became the largest oil producer in the world, and oil from the North Sea and Alaska flooded the market.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] In November 1978, a strike by 37,000 workers at Iran's nationalized oil refineries reduced production from 6 million barrels (950,000 m3) per day to about 1.5 million barrels (240,000 m3).
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] By bringing navy personnel into crude oil production operations, the government fixed short-term disruptions and by end of November the output came back to almost normal level.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] On January 16, 1979, the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, and his wife, Farah Pahlavi, left Iran at the behest of Prime Minister Shapour Bakhtiar, who sought to calm the situation.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] After the departure of the Shah, Ayatollah Khomeini became the new leader of Iran.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] The rise in oil prices benefited a few members of the Organization of Petroleum-Exporting Countries (OPEC), which made record profits.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Under the new Iranian government, oil exports later resumed but production was inconsistent and at a lower volume, further raising prices.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Saudi Arabia and other OPEC nations, under the presidency of Mana Al Otaiba, increased production to offset most of the decline, and by early 1979 the overall loss in worldwide production was roughly four percent.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] The war between Iran and Iraq in 1980 caused a further 7 percent drop in worldwide production.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] OPEC production was surpassed by other exporters such as the United States, as OPEC member nations were divided amongst themselves.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Saudi Arabia, a "swing producer", tried to gain back the market share after 1985, increasing production and causing downward pressure on prices, making high-cost oil production facilities less profitable.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] The oil crisis had a mixed impact on the United States.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Richard Nixon had imposed price controls on domestic oil as a result of the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Since then, gasoline price controls had been repealed, but those on domestic oil remained.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] The Jimmy Carter administration began a phased deregulation of oil prices on April 5, 1979, when the average price of crude oil was US$15.85 per barrel ($100/m3).
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Starting with the Iranian revolution, the price of crude oil rose to $39.50 per barrel ($248/m3) over the next 12 months (its all-time highest real price until March 3, 2008).
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Deregulating domestic oil price controls allowed U.S. oil output to rise sharply from the large Prudhoe Bay fields, while oil imports fell sharply.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Although not directly related, the near-disaster at Three Mile Island on March 28, 1979, also increased anxiety about energy policy and availability.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Due to memories of the oil shortage in 1973, motorists soon began panic buying, and long lines appeared at gas stations, as they had six years earlier.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] The average vehicle of the time consumed between two and three liters (about 0.5–0.8 gallons) of gasoline an hour while idling, and it was estimated that Americans wasted up to 150,000 barrels (24,000 m3) of oil per day idling their engines in the lines at gas stations.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] In 1979, the amount of oil sold in the United States was only 3.5 percent less than the record set for oil sold in 1978.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] A telephone poll of 1,600 American adults conducted by the Associated Press and NBC News and released in early May 1979 found that only 37 percent of Americans thought the energy shortages were real, nine percent were not sure, and 54 percent thought the energy shortages were a hoax.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Many politicians proposed gas rationing.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] One such proponent was Harry Hughes, Governor of Maryland, who proposed odd-even rationing (only people with an odd-numbered license plate could purchase gas on an odd-numbered day), as was used during the 1973 Oil Crisis.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Several states implemented odd-even gas rationing, including California, Pennsylvania, New York, New Jersey, Oregon, and Texas.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Coupons for gasoline rationing were printed but were never actually used during the 1979 crisis.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] On July 15, 1979, President Carter outlined his plans to reduce oil imports and improve energy efficiency in his "Crisis of Confidence" speech, sometimes known as the "malaise" speech.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] In the speech, Carter encouraged citizens to do what they could to reduce their use of energy.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] He had already installed water tank heating solar panels on the roof of the White House and a wood-burning stove in the living quarters.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] The panels were removed in 1986, reportedly for roof maintenance, during the administration of his successor, Ronald Reagan.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] A speech Carter gave in April 1977 argued that the oil crisis was "the moral equivalent of war".
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] In November 1979, Iranian revolutionaries seized the American Embassy, and Carter imposed an embargo on Iranian oil.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] In January 1980, he issued the Carter Doctrine, declaring: "An attempt by any outside force to gain control of the Persian Gulf region will be regarded as an assault on the vital interests of the United States".
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Additionally, as part of his administration's efforts at deregulation, Carter proposed removing price controls that had been imposed by the Richard Nixon administration before the 1973 crisis.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Carter agreed to remove price controls in phases.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] They were fully dismantled in 1981 under Reagan.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Carter also said he would impose a windfall profit tax on oil companies.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] While the regulated price of domestic oil was kept to $6 a barrel, the world market price was $30.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] In 1980, the U.S. government established the Synthetic Fuels Corporation to produce an alternative to imported fossil fuels.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] When the price of West Texas Intermediate crude oil increased 250 percent between 1978 and 1980, the oil-producing areas of Texas, Oklahoma, Louisiana, Colorado, Wyoming, and Alaska began experiencing an economic boom and population inflows.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] According to a 2019 study, individuals who were between the ages of 15 and 18 during the 1979 oil crisis were substantially less likely to use cars once they were in their mid-30s.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] In response to the high oil prices of the 1970s, industrial nations took steps to reduce their dependence on the Organization of Petroleum-Exporting Countries (OPEC) oil.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Electric utilities worldwide switched from oil to coal, natural gas, or nuclear power.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] National governments initiated multibillion-dollar research programs to develop alternatives to oil and commercial exploration developed major non-OPEC oilfields in Siberia, Alaska, North Sea, and the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] By 1986, daily worldwide demand for oil dropped by 5 million barrels but, non-OPEC production rose by an even-larger amount.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Consequently, OPEC's market share reduced from 50 percent in 1979 to 29 percent in 1985.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] At the time, Detroit's "Big Three" automakers (Ford, Chrysler, GM) were marketing downsized full-sized automobiles like the Chevrolet Caprice, the Ford LTD Crown Victoria and the Dodge St.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Regis which met the CAFE fuel economy mandates passed in 1978.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Detroit's response to the growing popularity of imported compacts like the Toyota Corolla and the Volkswagen Rabbit was the Chevrolet Citation and the Ford Fairmont.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Ford replaced the Ford Pinto with the Ford Escort and Chrysler, on the verge of bankruptcy, introduced the Dodge Aries K.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] GM was having unfavorable market reactions to the Citation and introduced the Chevrolet Corsica and Chevrolet Beretta in 1987 which sold better.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] GM also replaced the Chevrolet Monza, introducing the 1982 Chevrolet Cavalier which was better received.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Ford experienced a similar market rejection of the Fairmont and introduced the front-wheel-drive Ford Tempo in 1984.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Detroit was not well prepared for the sudden rise in fuel prices, and imported brands, primarily the Asian models, which were mass-marketed and had a lower manufacturing cost as opposed to British and West German brands.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] A year after the 1979 Iranian Revolution, Japanese manufacturers surpassed Detroit's production totals, becoming first in the world.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] The share of Japanese cars in U.S. auto purchases rose from 9 percent in 1976 to 21 percent in 1980.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Japanese exports later displaced the automotive market once dominated by lower-tier European manufacturers (Renault, Fiat, Opel, Peugeot, MG, Triumph, Citroen).
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Triumph, Simca) or withdraw from the U.S. market, especially in the wake of grey market automobiles or the inability of the vehicle to meet DOT requirements, from emission requirements to automotive lighting.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] Many imported brands utilized fuel-saving technologies such as fuel injection and multi-valve engines over the common use of carburetors.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] The overall fuel economy of cars in the United States increased from about 15 miles per US gallon (16 L/100 km; 18 mpg‑imp) in 1979 to 18 mpg‑US (13 L/100 km; 22 mpg‑imp) by 1985 and 20 mpg‑US (12 L/100 km; 24 mpg‑imp) by 1990.
[src:new-zealand/1979-oil-crisis] This was one factor leading to the subsequent 1980s oil glut.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The islands of New Zealand were the last large habitable land to be settled by humans.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Between about 1280 and 1350, Polynesians began to settle in the islands and subsequently developed a distinctive Māori culture.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1642, the Dutch explorer Abel Tasman became the first European to sight and record New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1769, the British explorer Captain James Cook became the first European to set foot on and map New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1840, representatives of the United Kingdom and Māori chiefs signed the Treaty of Waitangi, which paved the way for Britain's declaration of sovereignty later that year and the establishment of the Crown Colony of New Zealand in 1841.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Subsequently, a series of conflicts between the colonial government and Māori tribes resulted in the alienation and confiscation of large amounts of Māori land.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand became a dominion in 1907; it gained full statutory independence in 1947, retaining the monarch as head of state.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Today, the majority of New Zealand's population of around 5.3 million is of European descent; the indigenous Māori are the largest minority, followed by Asians and Pasifika.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Reflecting this, New Zealand's culture mainly derives from Māori and early British settlers but has recently broadened from increased immigration.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The official languages are English, Māori, and New Zealand Sign Language, with the local dialect of English being dominant.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] A developed country, New Zealand was the first to introduce a minimum wage and to give women the right to vote.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Recognised as a middle power, New Zealand ranks very highly in international measures of quality of life and human rights and has one of the lowest levels of perceived corruption in the world.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] It retains visible levels of inequality, including structural disparities between its Māori and European populations.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] During the 1980s, New Zealand underwent major economic changes that transformed it from a protectionist to a liberalised free-trade economy.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The service sector dominates the country's economy, followed by the industrial sector, and agriculture; international tourism is also a significant source of revenue.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand and Australia have a strong relationship and are considered to share a strong Trans-Tasman identity, stemming from centuries of British colonisation.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The country is part of multiple international organisations and forums.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Nationally, legislative authority is vested in an elected, unicameral Parliament, while executive political power is exercised by the Government, led by the prime minister, currently Christopher Luxon.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Charles III is the country's king and is represented by the governor-general, Cindy Kiro.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand is organised into 11 regional councils and 67 territorial authorities for local government purposes.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The Realm of New Zealand also includes Tokelau (a dependent territory); the Cook Islands and Niue (self-governing states in free association with New Zealand); and the Ross Dependency, which is New Zealand's territorial claim in Antarctica.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The first European visitor to New Zealand, Dutch explorer Abel Tasman, named the islands *Staten Land*, believing they were part of the *Staten Landt* that Jacob Le Maire had sighted off the southern end of South America.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The next year, in 1643, Hendrik Brouwer proved that the South American land was just a small island, and Dutch cartographers subsequently renamed Tasman's discovery *Nova Zeelandia* from Latin, after the Dutch province of Zeeland.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] This name was later anglicised to *New Zealand*.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] This was written as *Nu Tireni* in the Māori language (spelt *Nu Tirani* in Te Tiriti o Waitangi).
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1834, a document written in Māori, "*He Wakaputanga o te Rangatiratanga o Nu Tireni*", was translated into English and became the Declaration of the Independence of New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] It was prepared by *Te W(h)akaminenga o Nga Rangatiratanga o Nga Hapu o Nu Tireni*, the United Tribes of New Zealand, and a copy was sent to King William IV, who had already acknowledged the flag of the United Tribes of New Zealand and who recognised the declaration in a letter from Lord Glenelg.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1830, mapmakers began to use "North" and "South" on their maps to distinguish the two largest islands, and by 1907, this was the accepted norm.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The New Zealand Geographic Board discovered in 2009 that the names of the North Island and South Island had never been formalised, and names and alternative names were formalised in 2013.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] This set the names as *North Island* or *Te Ika-a-Māui*, and *South Island* or *Te Waipounamu*.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] For each island, either its English or Māori name can be used, or both can be used together.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Similarly the Māori and English names for the whole country are sometimes used together (*Aotearoa New Zealand*); however, this has no official recognition.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The first people to reach New Zealand were Polynesians in oceangoing *waka*, who are believed to have arrived in several waves between about 1280 and 1350.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] According to most Māori oral traditions, the islands were first discovered by the semi-legendary explorer Kupe while in pursuit of a giant octopus.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] These traditions hold that Kupe was followed by a great fleet of settlers, who set out from Hawaiki in eastern Polynesia around 1350.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The existence of a single great fleet that settled New Zealand has since been superseded by the belief that the majority of settlement was a planned and deliberate event that occurred over several decades.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The exact date of this settlement is unclear, with recent sources favouring settlement in the 14th century.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] While mitochondrial DNA variability within Māori populations suggests that New Zealand was first settled between 1250 and 1300, no human remains, artefacts or structures can be reliably dated to earlier than the Kaharoa eruption of Mount Tarawera around 1314.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] This scenario is also consistent with a debated third line of oral evidence, traditional genealogies (*whakapapa*) that point to around 1350 as a probable arrival date for several of the migratory waka (canoes) from which many Māori trace their descent.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Some Māori later migrated to the Chatham Islands, where they developed their distinct Moriori culture; a later 1835 invasion by Māori iwi resulted in the massacre and virtual extinction of the Moriori.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In a hostile 1642 encounter between Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri and Abel Tasman's crew, four of Tasman's crew members were killed and at least one Māori was hit by canister shot.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Europeans did not revisit New Zealand until 1769, when British explorer James Cook mapped almost the entire coastline.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Following Cook, New Zealand was visited by numerous European and North American whaling, sealing, and trading ships.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] They traded European food, metal tools, weapons, and other goods for timber, Māori food, artefacts, and water.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The introduction of the potato and the musket transformed Māori agriculture and warfare.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Potatoes provided a reliable food surplus, which enabled longer and more sustained military campaigns.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The resulting intertribal Musket Wars encompassed over 600 battles between 1801 and 1840, killing 30,000–40,000 Māori.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] From the early 19th century, Christian missionaries began to settle New Zealand, eventually converting most of the Māori population.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The Māori population declined to around 40% of its pre-contact level during the 19th century; introduced diseases were the major factor.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The British Government appointed James Busby as British Resident to New Zealand in 1832.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] His duties, given to him by Governor Bourke in Sydney, were to protect settlers and traders "of good standing", prevent "outrages" against Māori, and apprehend escaped convicts.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1835, following an announcement of impending French settlement by Charles de Thierry, the nebulous United Tribes of New Zealand sent a Declaration of Independence to King William IV of the United Kingdom asking for protection.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The Colonial Office sent Captain William Hobson to claim British sovereignty and negotiate a treaty with the Māori, prompted by growing unrest, the New Zealand Company's land-buying survey, and the legal ambiguity of the 1835 Declaration of Independence.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The Treaty of Waitangi was first signed in the Bay of Islands on 6 February 1840.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In response to the New Zealand Company's attempts to establish an independent settlement in Wellington, Hobson declared British sovereignty over all of New Zealand on 21 May 1840, even though copies of the treaty were still circulating throughout the country for Māori to sign.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] With the signing of the treaty and declaration of sovereignty, the number of immigrants, particularly from the United Kingdom, began to increase.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand was administered as a dependency of the Colony of New South Wales until becoming a separate Crown colony, the Colony of New Zealand, on 3 May 1841.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Armed conflict began between the colonial government and Māori in 1843 with the Wairau Affray over land and disagreements over sovereignty.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] These conflicts, mainly in the North Island, saw thousands of imperial troops and the Royal Navy come to New Zealand and became known as the New Zealand Wars.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Following these armed conflicts, large areas of Māori land were confiscated by the government.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The colony gained a representative government in 1852, and the first Parliament met in 1854.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1856 the colony effectively became self-governing, gaining responsibility over all domestic matters, except native policy, which was granted in the mid-1860s.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Following concerns that the South Island might form a separate colony, premier Alfred Domett moved a resolution to transfer the capital from Auckland to a locality near Cook Strait.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Wellington was chosen for its central location, with Parliament officially sitting there for the first time in 1865.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] As a result, instructions were issued directing the Admiral on the Australian Station to hoist the British flag on the Kermadecs, which lie about 1,000 km (620 mi) northeast of Auckland.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Since 1937, the islands have been uninhabited except for about six people at Raoul Island station.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] These islands put the northern border of New Zealand at 29 degrees South latitude.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] After the 1982 UNCLOS, the islands contributed significantly to New Zealand's exclusive economic zone.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1891, the Liberal Party came to power as the first organised political party.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The Liberal Government, led by Richard Seddon for most of its period in office, passed many important social and economic measures.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1893, New Zealand was the first nation in the world to grant all women the right to vote and pioneered the adoption of compulsory arbitration between employers and unions in 1894.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The Liberals also guaranteed a minimum wage in 1894, a world first.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1907, at the request of the New Zealand Parliament, King Edward VII proclaimed New Zealand a Dominion within the British Empire, reflecting its self-governing status.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] At the 1926 Imperial Conference, the Prime Ministers of the Dominions declared that Britain should provide them equal sovereignty to it.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1947, New Zealand adopted the Statute of Westminster implementing the declaration, confirming that the British Parliament could no longer legislate for the country without its consent.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The British government's residual legislative powers were later removed by the Constitution Act 1986, and final rights of appeal to British courts were abolished in 2003.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Early in the 20th century, New Zealand was involved in world affairs, fighting in the First and Second World Wars and suffering through the Great Depression.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The depression led to the election of the first Labour Government and the establishment of a comprehensive welfare state and a protectionist economy.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand experienced increasing prosperity following the Second World War, and Māori began to leave their traditional rural life and move to the cities in search of work.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] A Māori protest movement developed, which criticised Eurocentrism and worked for greater recognition of Māori culture and of the Treaty of Waitangi.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1975, the Waitangi Tribunal was set up to investigate alleged breaches of the Treaty, and it was enabled to investigate historic grievances in 1985.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The government has negotiated settlements of these grievances with many iwi, although Māori claims to the foreshore and seabed proved controversial in the 2000s.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand is near the centre of the water hemisphere and is made up of two main islands and more than 700 smaller islands.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The two main islands (the North Island, or *Te Ika-a-Māui*, and the South Island, or *Te Waipounamu*) are separated by Cook Strait, 22 kilometres (14 mi) wide at its narrowest point.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Besides the North and South Islands, the five largest inhabited islands are Stewart Island (across the Foveaux Strait), Chatham Island, Great Barrier Island (in the Hauraki Gulf), D'Urville Island (in the Marlborough Sounds) and Waiheke Island (about 22 km (14 mi) from central Auckland).
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The nearest continent is Australia to the west north west, with the shortest distance between the Australian and New Zealand mainlands being roughly 1,487 kilometers (924 miles) across the Tasman Sea, specifically between Tasmania and Fiordland.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The closest point between any territory of both countries is between Macquarie Island (Australia) and Auckland Island (New Zealand), which are about 618 kilometers (384 miles) apart.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand is long and narrow—over 1,600 kilometres (990 mi) along its north-north-east axis with a maximum width of 400 kilometres (250 mi)—with about 15,000 km (9,300 mi) of coastline and a total land area of 268,000 square kilometres (103,500 sq mi).
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Because of its far-flung outlying islands and long coastline, the country has extensive marine resources.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Its exclusive economic zone is one of the world's largest, covering more than 15 times its land area.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The South Island is the largest landmass of New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] It is divided along its length by the Southern Alps.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] There are 18 peaks over 3,000 metres (9,800 ft), the highest of which is Aoraki / Mount Cook at 3,724 metres (12,218 ft).
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Fiordland's steep mountains and deep fiords record the extensive ice age glaciation of this southwestern corner of the South Island.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The North Island is less mountainous but is marked by volcanism.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The highly active Taupō Volcanic Zone has formed a large volcanic plateau, punctuated by the North Island's highest mountain, Mount Ruapehu (2,797 metres (9,177 ft)).
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The plateau also hosts the country's largest lake, Lake Taupō, nestled in the caldera of one of the world's most active supervolcanoes.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The country owes its varied topography, and perhaps even its emergence above the waves, to the dynamic boundary it straddles between the Pacific and Indo-Australian Plates.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand is part of Zealandia, a microcontinent nearly half the size of Australia that gradually submerged after breaking away from the Gondwanan supercontinent.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] About 25 million years ago, a shift in plate tectonic movements began to contort and crumple the region.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] This is now most evident in the Southern Alps, formed by compression of the crust beside the Alpine Fault.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Elsewhere, the plate boundary involves the subduction of one plate under the other, producing the Puysegur Trench to the south, the Hikurangi Trough east of the North Island, and the Kermadec and Tonga Trenches further north.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand, together with Australia, is part of a wider region known as Australasia.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] It also forms the southwestern extremity of the geographic and ethnographic region called Polynesia.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Oceania is a wider region encompassing the Australian continent, New Zealand, and various island countries in the Pacific Ocean that are not included in the seven-continent model.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand's climate is predominantly temperate maritime (Köppen: Cfb), with mean annual temperatures ranging from 10 °C (50 °F) in the south to 16 °C (61 °F) in the north.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Historical maxima and minima are 42.4 °C (108.32 °F) in Rangiora, Canterbury and −25.6 °C (−14.08 °F) in Ranfurly, Otago.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Conditions vary sharply across regions, from extremely wet on the West Coast of the South Island to semi-arid in Central Otago and the Mackenzie Basin of inland Canterbury and subtropical in Northland.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Of the seven largest cities, Christchurch is the driest, receiving on average only 618 millimetres (24.3 in) of rain per year.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Wellington is the wettest, receiving almost twice that amount.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Auckland, Wellington and Christchurch all receive a yearly average of more than 2,000 hours of sunshine.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The southern and southwestern parts of the South Island have a cooler and cloudier climate, with around 1,400–1,600 hours.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The northern and northeastern parts of the South Island are the sunniest areas of the country and receive about 2,400–2,500 hours.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The general snow season is early June until early October, though cold snaps can occur outside this season.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Snowfall is common in the eastern and southern parts of the South Island and mountain areas across the country.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand's geographic isolation for 80 million years and island biogeography has influenced evolution of the country's species of animals, fungi and plants.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Physical isolation has caused biological isolation, resulting in a dynamic evolutionary ecology with examples of distinctive plants and animals as well as populations of widespread species.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The flora and fauna of New Zealand were originally thought to have originated from New Zealand's fragmentation off from Gondwana; however, more recent evidence postulates species resulted from dispersal.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] About 82% of New Zealand's indigenous vascular plants are endemic, covering 1,944 species across 65 genera.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The number of fungi recorded from New Zealand, including lichen-forming species, is not known, nor is the proportion of those fungi which are endemic, but one estimate suggests there are about 2,300 species of lichen-forming fungi in New Zealand and 40% of these are endemic.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The two main types of forest are those dominated by broadleaf trees with emergent podocarps, or by southern beech in cooler climates.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The remaining vegetation types consist of grasslands, the majority of which are tussock.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Before humans arrived, an estimated 80% of the land was covered in forest, with only high alpine, wet, infertile and volcanic areas without trees.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Massive deforestation occurred after humans arrived, with around half the forest cover lost to fire after Polynesian settlement.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Much of the remaining forest fell after European settlement, being logged or cleared to make room for pastoral farming, leaving forest occupying only 23% of the land in 1997.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The forests were dominated by birds, and the lack of mammalian predators led to some, like the kiwi, kākāpō, weka and takahē, evolving flightlessness.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The arrival of humans, associated changes to habitat, and the introduction of rats, ferrets and other mammals led to the extinction of many bird species, including large birds like the moa and Haast's eagle.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Other indigenous animals are represented by reptiles (tuatara, skinks and geckos), frogs, such as the protected endangered Hamilton's Frog, spiders, insects (wētā), and snails.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Some, such as the tuatara, are so unique that they have been called living fossils.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Three species of bats (one since extinct) were the only sign of native land mammals in New Zealand until the 2006 discovery of bones from a unique, mouse-sized land mammal at least 16 million years old.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Marine mammals are abundant, with almost half the world's cetaceans (whales, dolphins, and porpoises) and large numbers of fur seals reported in New Zealand waters.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Many seabirds breed in New Zealand, a third of them unique to the country.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] More penguin species are found in New Zealand than in any other country, with 13 of the world's 18 penguin species.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Since human arrival, almost half of the country's vertebrate species have become extinct, including at least 51 birds, three frogs, three lizards, one freshwater fish, and one bat.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Others are endangered or have had their range severely reduced.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand conservationists have pioneered several methods to help threatened wildlife recover, including island sanctuaries, pest control, wildlife translocation, fostering, and ecological restoration of islands and other protected areas.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand is a constitutional monarchy with a parliamentary democracy, although its constitution is not codified.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Charles III is the King of New Zealand and thus the head of state.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The king is represented by the governor-general, whom he appoints on the advice of the prime minister.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The powers of the monarch and the governor-general are limited by constitutional constraints and cannot normally be exercised without the advice of ministers.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The New Zealand Parliament holds legislative power and consists of the king and the House of Representatives.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] It also included an upper house, the Legislative Council, until this was abolished in 1950.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The supremacy of parliament over the Crown and other government institutions was established in England by the Bill of Rights 1689 and has been ratified as law in New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The House of Representatives is democratically elected, and a government is formed from the party or coalition with the majority of seats.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] If no majority is formed, a minority government can be formed if support from other parties during confidence and supply votes is assured.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The governor-general appoints ministers under advice from the prime minister, who is by convention the parliamentary leader of the governing party or coalition.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Cabinet, formed by ministers and led by the prime minister, is the highest policy-making body in government and responsible for deciding significant government actions.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Members of Cabinet make major decisions collectively and are therefore collectively responsible for the consequences of these decisions.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The 42nd and current prime minister, since 27 November 2023, is Christopher Luxon.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] A parliamentary general election must be called no later than three years after the previous election.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Almost all general elections between 1853 and 1993 were held under the first-past-the-post voting system.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Since the 1996 election, a form of proportional representation called mixed-member proportional (MMP) has been used.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Under the MMP system, each person has two votes; one is for a candidate standing in the voter's electorate, and the other is for a party.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Elections since the 1930s have been dominated by two political parties, National and Labour.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] More parties have been represented in Parliament since the introduction of MMP.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand's judiciary, headed by the chief justice, includes the Supreme Court, Court of Appeal, the High Court, and subordinate courts.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Judges and judicial officers are appointed non-politically and under strict rules regarding tenure to help maintain judicial independence.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] This theoretically allows the judiciary to interpret the law based solely on the legislation enacted by Parliament without other influences on their decisions.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand is identified as one of the world's most stable and well-governed states.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] As of 2023, the country is ranked second in the strength of its democratic institutions, and third in government transparency and lack of corruption.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] LGBT rights in the nation are also recognised as among the most tolerant in Oceania.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand ranks highly for civic participation in the political process, with 82% voter turnout during recent general elections, compared to an OECD average of 69%.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] But this is untrue of local council elections; a historically low 36% of eligible New Zealanders voted in the 2022 local elections, compared with an already low 42% turnout in 2019.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] A 2017 human rights report by the United States Department of State noted that the New Zealand government generally respected the rights of individuals, but voiced concerns regarding the social status of the Māori population.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The New Zealand Human Rights Commission has asserted that there is strong, consistent evidence that structural discrimination is a real and ongoing socioeconomic issue.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] One example of structural inequality in New Zealand can be seen in the criminal justice system.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] According to the Ministry of Justice, Māori are overrepresented, comprising 45% of New Zealanders convicted of crimes and 53% of those imprisoned, while only being 16.5% of the population.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Under legislation passed in London, New Zealand was divided into six provinces in 1853.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Following further legislation shortly afterwards three further provinces were created from three of the original six, leaving the country with nine provinces in 1862, each with a degree of autonomy under an elected superintendent.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Because of financial pressures and the desire to consolidate railways, education, land sales, and other policies, government was centralised and the provinces were abolished in 1876.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The provinces are remembered in regional public holidays and sporting rivalries.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Since 1876, various councils have administered local areas under legislation determined by the central government.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1989, the government reorganised local government into the current two-tier structure of regional councils and territorial authorities.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The 249 municipalities that existed in 1975 have been consolidated into 67 territorial authorities and 11 regional councils.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The regional councils' role is to regulate "the natural environment with particular emphasis on resource management", while territorial authorities are responsible for sewage, water, local roads, building consents, and other local matters.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Five of the territorial councils are unitary authorities and also act as regional councils.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The territorial authorities consist of 13 city councils, 53 district councils, and the Chatham Islands Council.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] While officially the Chatham Islands Council is not a unitary authority, it undertakes many functions of a regional council.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The Realm of New Zealand, one of 15 Commonwealth realms, is the entire area over which the king or queen of New Zealand is sovereign and comprises New Zealand, Tokelau, the Ross Dependency, the Cook Islands, and Niue.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The Cook Islands and Niue are self-governing states in free association with New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The New Zealand Parliament cannot pass legislation for these countries, but with their consent can act on behalf of them in foreign affairs and defence.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Tokelau is classified as a non-self-governing territory, but is administered by a council of three elders (one from each Tokelauan atoll).
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The Ross Dependency is New Zealand's territorial claim in Antarctica, where it operates the Scott Base research facility.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand nationality law treats all parts of the realm equally, so most people born in New Zealand, the Cook Islands, Niue, Tokelau, and the Ross Dependency are New Zealand citizens.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] During the period of the New Zealand colony, Britain was responsible for external trade and foreign relations.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The 1923 and 1926 Imperial Conferences decided that New Zealand should be allowed to negotiate its own political treaties, and the first commercial treaty was ratified in 1928 with Japan.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] On 3 September 1939, New Zealand allied itself with Britain and declared war on Germany with Prime Minister Michael Joseph Savage proclaiming, "Where she goes, we go; where she stands, we stand".
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1951, New Zealand, Australia, and the US signed the ANZUS Treaty.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The influence of the United States on New Zealand weakened following protests over the Vietnam War, the refusal of the United States to admonish France after the sinking of the *Rainbow Warrior*, disagreements over environmental and agricultural trade issues, and New Zealand's nuclear-free policy.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Despite the United States's suspension of ANZUS obligations, the treaty remained in effect between New Zealand and Australia, whose foreign policy has followed a similar historical trend.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Close political contact is maintained between the two countries, with free trade agreements and travel arrangements that allow citizens to visit, live and work in both countries without restrictions.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 2013 there were about 650,000 New Zealand citizens living in Australia, which is equivalent to 15% of the population of New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand has a strong presence among the Pacific Island countries, and enjoys strong diplomatic relations with Samoa, Fiji, and Tonga, and among smaller nations.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] A large proportion of New Zealand's aid goes to these countries, and many Pacific people migrate to New Zealand for employment.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The increase of this since the 1960s led to the formation of the Pasifika New Zealander pan-ethnic group, the fourth-largest ethnic grouping in the country.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Permanent migration is regulated under the 1970 Samoan Quota Scheme and the 2002 Pacific Access Category, which allow up to 1,100 Samoan nationals and up to 750 other Pacific Islanders respectively to become permanent New Zealand residents each year.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] A seasonal workers scheme for temporary migration was introduced in 2007, and in 2009 about 8,000 Pacific Islanders were employed under it.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand is involved in the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations Regional Forum (including the East Asia Summit).
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand has been described as a middle power in the Asia-Pacific region, and an emerging power.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The country is a member of the United Nations, the Commonwealth of Nations and the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), and participates in the Five Power Defence Arrangements.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Today, New Zealand enjoys particularly close relations with the United States and is one of its major non-NATO allies, as well as with Australia, with a "Trans-Tasman" identity between citizens of the latter being common.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand is a member of the Five Eyes intelligence sharing agreement, known formally as the UKUSA Agreement.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The five members of this agreement comprise the core Anglosphere: Australia, Canada, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Since 2012, New Zealand has had a partnership arrangement with NATO under the Partnership Interoperability Initiative.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] According to the 2024 Global Peace Index, New Zealand is the 4th most peaceful country in the world.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand's military services—the New Zealand Defence Force—comprise the New Zealand Army, the Royal New Zealand Air Force and the Royal New Zealand Navy.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand's national defence needs are modest since a direct attack is unlikely.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] However, its military has had a global presence.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The country fought in both world wars, with notable campaigns in Gallipoli, Crete, El Alamein, and Monte Cassino.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The Gallipoli campaign played an important part in fostering New Zealand's national identity and strengthened the ANZAC tradition it shares with Australia.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In addition the two world wars, New Zealand fought in the Second Boer War, the Korean War, the Malayan Emergency, the Vietnam War, the Gulf War, and the Afghanistan War.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] It has contributed forces to several regional and global peacekeeping missions, such as those in Cyprus, Somalia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, the Sinai, Angola, Cambodia, the Iran–Iraq border, Bougainville, East Timor, and the Solomon Islands.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand has an advanced market economy, ranked 16th in the 2022 Human Development Index, and fourth in the 2022 Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Historically, extractive industries have contributed strongly to New Zealand's economy, focusing at different times on sealing, whaling, flax, gold, kauri gum, and native timber.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The first shipment of refrigerated meat on the *Dunedin* in 1882 led to the establishment of meat and dairy exports to Britain, a trade which provided the basis for strong economic growth in New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] High demand for agricultural products from the United Kingdom and the United States helped New Zealanders achieve higher living standards than both Australia and Western Europe in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 1973, New Zealand's export market was reduced when the United Kingdom joined the European Economic Community and other compounding factors, such as the 1973 oil and 1979 energy crises, led to a severe economic depression.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Living standards in New Zealand fell behind those of Australia and Western Europe, and by 1982 New Zealand had the lowest per-capita income of all the developed nations surveyed by the World Bank.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In the mid-1980s New Zealand deregulated its agricultural sector by phasing out subsidies over a three-year period.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Since 1984, successive governments engaged in major macroeconomic restructuring (known first as Rogernomics and then Ruthanasia), rapidly transforming New Zealand from a protectionist and highly regulated economy to a liberalised free-trade economy.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Unemployment peaked just above 10% in 1991 and 1992, following the 1987 share market crash, but eventually fell to 3.7% in 2007 (ranking third from twenty-seven comparable OECD nations).
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] However, the 2008 financial crisis had a major effect on New Zealand, with the GDP shrinking for five consecutive quarters, the longest recession in over thirty years, and unemployment rising back to 7% in late 2009.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The lowest unemployment rate recorded using the current methodology was in December 2021 during the COVID-19 pandemic, at 3.2%.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Unemployment rates for different age groups follow similar trends but are consistently higher among youth.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] During the September 2021 quarter, the general unemployment rate was around 3.2%, while the unemployment rate for youth aged 15 to 24 was 9.2%.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand has experienced a series of "brain drains" since the 1970s that still continue today.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Nearly one-quarter of highly skilled workers live overseas, mostly in Australia and Britain, which is the largest proportion from any developed nation.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In recent decades, however, a "brain gain" has brought in educated professionals from Europe and less developed countries.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Today New Zealand's economy benefits from a high level of innovation.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Moreover, child poverty in New Zealand has been identified by the Government as a major societal issue; the country has 12.0% of children living in low-income households that have less than 50% of the median equivalised disposable household income as of June 2022.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Poverty has a disproportionately high effect in ethnic-minority households, with a quarter (23.3%) of Māori children and almost a third (28.6%) of Pacific Islander children living in poverty as of 2020.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand is heavily dependent on international trade, particularly in agricultural products.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Exports account for 24% of its output, making New Zealand vulnerable to international commodity prices and global economic slowdowns.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Food products made up 55% of the value of all the country's exports in 2014; wood was the second largest earner (7%).
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand's main trading partners, as at June 2018, are China (NZ$27.8b), Australia ($26.2b), the European Union ($22.9b), the United States ($17.6b), and Japan ($8.4b).
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] On 7 April 2008, New Zealand and China signed the New Zealand–China Free Trade Agreement, the first such agreement China has signed with a developed country.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In July 2023, New Zealand and the European Union entered into the EU–New Zealand Free Trade Agreement, which eliminated tariffs on several goods traded between the two regions.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] This free trade agreement expanded on the pre-existing free trade agreement and saw a reduction in tariffs on meat and dairy in response to feedback from the affected industries.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The service sector is the largest sector in the economy, followed by manufacturing and construction and then farming and raw material extraction.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Tourism plays a significant role in the economy, contributing $12.9 billion (or 5.6%) to New Zealand's total GDP and supporting 7.5% of the total workforce in 2016.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 2017, international visitor arrivals were expected to increase at a rate of 5.4% annually up to 2022.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Wool was New Zealand's major agricultural export during the late 19th century.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Even as late as the 1960s it made up over a third of all export revenues, but since then its price has steadily dropped relative to other commodities, and wool is no longer profitable for many farmers.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In contrast, dairy farming increased, with the number of dairy cows doubling between 1990 and 2007, to become New Zealand's largest export earner.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In the year to June 2018, dairy products accounted for 17.7% ($14.1 billion) of total exports, and the country's largest company, Fonterra, controls almost one-third of the international dairy trade.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand's wine industry has followed a similar trend to dairy, the number of vineyards doubling over the same period, overtaking wool exports for the first time in 2007.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] In 2015, renewable energy generated 40.1% of New Zealand's gross energy supply.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The majority of the country's electricity supply is generated from hydroelectric power, with major schemes on the Waikato, Waitaki and Clutha / Mata-Au rivers, as well as at Manapouri.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Geothermal power is also a significant generator of electricity, with several large stations located across the Taupō Volcanic Zone in the North Island.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The four main companies in the generation and retail market are Contact Energy, Genesis Energy, Mercury Energy and Meridian Energy.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] State-owned Transpower operates the high-voltage transmission grids in the North and South Islands, as well as the Inter-Island HVDC link connecting the two together.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The provision of water supply and sanitation is generally of good quality.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Regional authorities provide water abstraction, treatment and distribution infrastructure to most developed areas.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand's transport network comprises 94,000 kilometres (58,410 mi) of roads, including 199 kilometres (124 mi) of motorways, and 4,128 kilometres (2,565 mi) of railway lines.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Most major cities and towns are linked by bus services, although the private car is the predominant mode of transport.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The country's railways were privatised in 1993 but were re-nationalised by the government in stages between 2004 and 2008.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The state-owned enterprise KiwiRail now operates the railways, with the exception of commuter services in Auckland and Wellington, which are operated by Auckland One Rail and Transdev Wellington respectively.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Railways run the length of the country, although most lines now carry freight rather than passengers.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The road and rail networks in the two main islands are linked by roll-on/roll-off ferries between Wellington and Picton, operated by Interislander (part of KiwiRail) and Bluebridge.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Most international visitors arrive via air.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand has four international airports: Auckland, Christchurch, Queenstown and Wellington.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Only Auckland and Christchurch have runways long enough for aircraft capable of long haul flights to Asia and the Americas.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The New Zealand Post Office had a monopoly over telecommunications in New Zealand until 1987 when Telecom New Zealand was formed, initially as a state-owned enterprise and then privatised in 1990.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Chorus, which was split from Telecom (now Spark) in 2011, still owns the majority of the telecommunications infrastructure, but competition from other providers has increased.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] A large-scale rollout of gigabit-capable fibre to the premises, branded as Ultra-Fast Broadband, began in 2009 with a target of being available to 87% of the population by 2022.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] As of 2017, the United Nations International Telecommunication Union ranks New Zealand 13th in the development of information and communications infrastructure.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The accumulation of knowledge of agricultural practice and the effects of herbal remedies in the treatment of illness and disease by Māori *tohunga* as well as their precise observation of nature might be considered an indigenous contribution to science in New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Cook's voyages in the 1700s and Darwin's in 1835 had important scientific botanical and zoological objectives.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Crown Research Institutes (CRIs) were formed in 1992 from existing government-owned research organisations.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Their role is to research and develop new science, knowledge, products and services across the economic, environmental, social and cultural spectrum for the benefit of New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The total gross expenditure on research and development (R&D) as a proportion of GDP rose to 1.37% in 2018, up from 1.23% in 2015.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand ranks 21st in the OECD for its gross R&D spending as a percentage of GDP.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] New Zealand was ranked 26th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] The New Zealand Space Agency was created by the government in 2016 for space policy, regulation and sector development.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Rocket Lab was the first commercial rocket launcher in the country.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Most private and commercial research organisations in New Zealand focus on the agricultural and fisheries sectors.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p01] Examples include the Cawthron Institute, the Livestock Improvement Corporation, the Fonterra Research and Development Centre, the Bragato Research Institute, the Kiwifruit Breeding Centre, and B+LNZ Genetics.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The 2023 New Zealand census enumerated a resident population of 4,993,923, an increase of 6.3% over the 2018 census figure.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] As of July 2026, the total population has risen to an estimated 5,351,800.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] New Zealand's population increased at a rate of 1.9% per year in the seven years ended June 2020.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] In September 2020 Statistics New Zealand reported that the population had climbed above 5 million people in September 2019, according to population estimates based on the 2018 census.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] New Zealand's population today is concentrated to the north of the country, with around 76.4% of the population living in the North Island and 23.6% in the South Island as of June 2025.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] During the 20th century, New Zealand's population drifted north.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] In 1921, the country's median centre of population was in the Tasman Sea west of Levin in Manawatū-Whanganui; by 2017, it had moved 280 km (170 mi) north to near Kawhia in Waikato.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] New Zealand is a predominantly urban country, with 84.5% of the population living in urban areas and 51.4% in the seven cities with populations exceeding 100,000.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Auckland, with over 1.4 million residents, is by far the largest city.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] New Zealand cities generally rank highly on international livability measures.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] For instance, in 2016, Auckland was ranked the world's third most liveable city and Wellington the twelfth by the Mercer Quality of Living Survey.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The median age of the New Zealand population at the 2018 census was 37.4 years, with life expectancy in 2017–2019 being 80.0 years for males and 83.5 years for females.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] While New Zealand is experiencing sub-replacement fertility, with a total fertility rate of 1.6 in 2020, the fertility rate is above the OECD average.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] By 2050, the median age is projected to rise to 43 years and the percentage of people 60 years of age and older to rise from 18% to 29%.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] In the 2023 census, 62.1% of residents responded as being ethnically New Zealand European, and 17.8% responded as being ethnically Māori.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Other major ethnicities include Chinese (5.2%), Indian (5.1%), Samoan (4.3%), Filipino (2.2%), Tongan (2.0%), Cook Islands Maori (1.9%), and English (1.4%) 13.2% responded with multiple ethnicities, with 8.2% alone responding as both European and Māori.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Statistics New Zealand allows people to choose multiple ethnicities and reports ethnic data based on total responses, therefore ethnicities add up to more than 100%.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] For legacy systems which can only accept one ethnicity, people are usually allocated to a single ethnicity based on a pre-determined priority order, with Māori given highest priority and New Zealand European given lowest priority.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The population has become more multicultural and diverse in recent decades: in 1961, the census reported that the population of New Zealand was 92% European and 7% Māori, with Asian and Pacific minorities sharing the remaining 1%.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] However, New Zealand's non-European population is disproportionately concentrated in the North Island and especially in the Auckland Region: while Auckland is home to 33% of New Zealand's population, it is home to 62% of the country's Pasifika population and 60% of its Asian population.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] While the demonym for a New Zealand citizen is New Zealander, the informal "Kiwi" is commonly used both internationally and by locals.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The Māori loanword *Pākehā* has been used to refer to New Zealanders of European descent, although some reject this name.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The word today is increasingly used to refer to all non-Polynesian New Zealanders.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The Māori were the first people to reach New Zealand, followed by the early European settlers.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Following colonisation, immigrants were predominantly from Britain, Ireland and Australia because of restrictive policies similar to the White Australia policy.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] There was also significant Dutch, Dalmatian, German, and Italian immigration, together with indirect European immigration through Australia, North America, South America and South Africa.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Net migration increased after the Second World War; in the 1970s and 1980s policies on immigration were relaxed, and immigration from Asia was promoted.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] In 2009–10, an annual target of 45,000–50,000 permanent residence approvals was set by the New Zealand Immigration Service—more than one new migrant for every 100 New Zealand residents.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] In the 2023 census, 28.8% of people counted were not born in New Zealand, up from 27.4% in the 2018 census.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The most popular countries of origin for overseas-born residents were England (14.6%), mainland China (10.2%), India (10.0%), the Philippines (7.0%), South Africa (6.7%), Australia (6.1%), Fiji (4.8%) and Samoa (4.3%).
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The number of fee-paying international students and international exchange students increased sharply in the late 1990s, with more than 20,000 studying in public tertiary institutions in 2002.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] New Zealand achieved a record net migration gain of 135,500 people in the year ended October 2023.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Immigrants from India, China and the Philippines are the largest contributors to New Zealand's population growth.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] In 2025, New Zealand's net migration fell to its lowest level in more than a decade.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] According to Statistics New Zealand, the country recorded a net migration gain of 14,200 in 2025, down 9,600 from a year earlier.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] That marked the smallest annual increase since 2013, outside 2021, when borders were largely closed during the COVID-19 outbreak.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] English is the predominant language in New Zealand, spoken by 95.4% of the population.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] New Zealand English has a distinctive accent and lexicon.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] It is similar to Australian English, and many speakers from the Northern Hemisphere are unable to tell the accents apart.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] After World War II, Māori were discouraged or prohibited to speak their own language (*te reo Māori*) in schools and workplaces, and it existed as a community language only in a few remote areas.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The Native Schools Act 1867 required instruction in English in all schools, and while no official policy banned children from speaking Māori, many suffered physical abuse if they did.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The Māori language has recently undergone a process of revitalisation, being declared one of New Zealand's official languages in 1987, and is spoken by 4.0% of the population.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Māori-language immersion schools and two Māori-language television channels now exist.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Many places have both their Māori and English names officially recognised.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] As recorded in the 2018 census, Samoan is the most widely spoken non-official language (2.2%), followed by "Northern Chinese" (including Mandarin, 2.0%), Hindi (1.5%), and French (1.2%).
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] New Zealand Sign Language was reported to be understood by 22,986 people (0.5%); it became one of New Zealand's official languages in 2006.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] According to the 2023 census, 51.6% of the "census usually resident population" had no religion, up from 48.2% in 2018 census.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Christians are the single largest religious group, forming 32.3% of the population, compared to 36.5% in 2018.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Hindus are the second largest religious minority, forming the 2.9% of population, followed by Muslims on 1.5%.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The Auckland Region exhibited the greatest religious diversity.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Primary and secondary schooling is compulsory for children aged 6 to 16, with the majority of children attending from the age of 5.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] There are 13 school years and attending state (public) schools is free to New Zealand citizens and permanent residents from a person's 5th birthday to the end of the calendar year following their 19th birthday.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] New Zealand has an adult literacy rate of 99%, and over half of the population aged 15 to 29 hold a tertiary qualification.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] There are five types of government-owned tertiary institutions: universities, colleges of education, polytechnics, specialist colleges, and wānanga, in addition to private training establishments.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] In 2021, in the population aged 25–64, 13% had no formal qualification, 21% had a school qualification, 28% had a tertiary certificate or diploma, and 35% have a bachelor's degree or higher.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The OECD's Programme for International Student Assessment ranks New Zealand as the 28th best in the OECD for maths, 13th best for science, and 11th best for reading.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] As of 2023, New Zealand allocated about 9.6 percent of its GDP to healthcare, slightly above the OECD average of 8.8 percent.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The public healthcare system operates under a publicly funded health insurance model that supports inpatient and outpatient services at public hospitals, along with preventive and primary care through private providers.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] *Health New Zealand – Te Whatu Ora* is the primary publicly funded healthcare system of New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The New Zealand Government established it to replace the country's 20 district health boards (DHBs) on 1 July 2022.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Health New Zealand is charged with working alongside the Public Health Agency to manage the provision of healthcare services in New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] As of 2022, the agency is New Zealand's largest employer, consolidating the DHBs' combined work force of 80,000, with an estimated annual operating budget of NZ$20 billion and an asset base of about NZ$24 billion.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Ischaemic heart disease is the leading cause of death, followed by Alzheimer disease and other dementias, and stroke.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The life expectancy has improved from 78.6 years in 2000 to 82.2 years in 2021.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Statistics have shown around 20% of New Zealanders identify with more than one ethnic group.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Around 80% are of European descent, 15% Maori, and others coming from China, the Pacific Islands and elsewhere.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The British and Irish immigrants brought aspects of their own culture to New Zealand and also influenced Māori culture, particularly with the introduction of Christianity.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] However, Māori still regard their allegiance to tribal groups as a vital part of their identity, and Māori kinship roles resemble those of other Polynesian peoples.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] More recently, American, Australian, Asian and other European cultures have exerted influence on New Zealand.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Non-Māori Polynesian cultures are also apparent, with Pasifika, the world's largest Polynesian festival, now an annual event in Auckland.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] The largely rural life in early New Zealand led to the image of New Zealanders as rugged, industrious problem solvers.
[src:new-zealand/new-zealand-p02] Modesty was expected and enforced through the "tall poppy syndrome", where high achievers received harsh criticism.
